\section{Introduction}

Functional logic programming has a long history and a rich literature.
But it is somewhat tricky for programmers to reason about functional logic programs: they must think about
logical variables, narrowing, backtracking, and the like.   This contrasts with functional programming,
where one can say ``just apply rewrite rules, such as beta reduction, let-inlining, and case-of-known-constructor''.
Moreover, these rewrite rules apply even in the presence of free variables; that is, under lambdas.

We therefore seek a completely-precise expression of functional logic programming, as
at term rewriting system, to give us both a formal semantics (via a small-step reductions),
and a powerful set of equvalences that programmers can use to reason about their programs,
and compilers can use to optimise them.

Our main contribution is a new core calculus for functional logic programming that
has the following properties:
\begin{itemize}
\item It has a small-step term rewriting semantics for a functional logic langauge
  that supports both narrowing and residuation.
  Just like rewriting for the lambda calculus, this semantics allows programmers to reason, step by step, about how their program executes.
\item It natively supports higher-order programming, just like the lambda calculus.  In contrast,
  the functional-logic literature typically addresses higher order features via defunctionalisation \cite[3.3]{hanus-survey}.
\item It supports so-called non-deterministic programming; that is, an expression can return one result, many results, or no result (failure).
  As a result, it natively supports both narrowing and residuation.
\end{itemize}
There is a rich seam of related work; an excellent starting point is Hanus's survey \cite{hanus:survey}.
We discuss related work in \Cref{sec:related}.


