We begin by presenting the Verse calculus informally.  We will give its
rewrite rules precisely in \Cref{sec:rewrite-rules}

\subsection{Syntax}

The syntax of the Verse calculus is given in \Cref{fig:verse-syntax}.
There is a core sub-language that is just the lambda-calculus with
some built-in operations and data constructors:
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Head normal forms}.
A head normal form, |hnf|, is a conventional value: a built-in constant |k| or operator |op|, a saturated
constructor application |con K (v1,dots,vn)|, or a lambda term |lam x e|.
For the built-in constants and operators we use only integer constants, and two representative
\item \emph{Values.}
In a functional logic language an expression may evaluate to an as-yet-unknown logical variable,
so a \emph{value} |v| is either a head normal form, or a variable |x|.
\item \emph{Expressions} |e| includes values |v|, an applications |applyx v1 v2|.  Remembering that
a value can be a lambda, that gives us the full lambda calculus.
\end{itemize}
But expressions also include two other key collections of constructs.
First, \emph{logical variables and unification}:
you can bring a fresh logical variable into scope with |defKW|; unify two expressions with |e1 = e2|; and
sequence two expressions with |e1 ; e2|.
As an example, what might be written |let x e1 e2| in a conventional functional language can be written
|def x (x=e1; e2)| in the Verse calculus.

